<p>
    <strong>PLUS, (Parent Loan for Undergraduate Student)</strong>
</p>
<p>
    First; to qualify the student has to be a dependent student and be enrolled at least half time.
</p>
<p>
    This loan is quite simple. It is in the parents name only; the child has no legal responsibility in relation to repayment. The parent borrows the loan on
    behalf of the child up to the maximum amount the child needs to attend college. There are no income requirements to obtain a PLUS loan. However there are
    credit requirements. Think of it is the 5 year rule, no bankruptcies, even starting of a foreclosure, charge-off, or repossession in that time period.
    Additionally, the student can have no adverse credit. The interest rate is 7.9%. The repayment period varies based on the amount of the loan and will be
    discussed during the application process, that said the maximum repayment period is 20 years.
</p>
<p>
    Finally: IF THE PARENT IS TURNED DOWN FOR A PLUS LOAN, the dependent student is automatically qualify for the higher independent maximum Stafford loans
    limits.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Private Loans</strong>
</p>
<p>
    Private student loans are an entirely different ball of wax. To start with keep in mind that the Credit Card industry is more tightly regulated that the
    Private Student Loan Industry. Additionally, the default rates on these types of loans are quite high and thus they are quite expensive. If however, the
    parent has good credit, private loans offer a very quick and easy way to obtain funds to pay for college. Most lenders have pulled out of the Private
    student loan market. However, there are several large lenders that do still offer the loans; a simple internet search will allow the parent to decide if
    such options are in his or her best interest.
</p>






